Of Pardons & Prison

The other big Sunday show debate concerned pardons and prosecutions. Last w=
eek, Trump told MTP=E2=80=99s Welker that House members who investigated th=
e January 6 insurrection should go to jail. This week, Welker asked Graham =
if he agreed, to which the senator simply answered, =E2=80=9CNo.=E2=80=9D (=
=E2=80=9CThat was very clear and concise,=E2=80=9D Welker responded.) Sande=
rs, appearing directly after Graham, offered more color. =E2=80=9CThis is w=
hat authoritarianism is all about. It=E2=80=99s what dictatorship is all ab=
out,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CYou do not arrest elected officials who dis=
agree with you, who undertake an investigation.=E2=80=9D

Of course, the prospect of politically motivated prosecutions=E2=80=94what =
Trump and his allies have characterized as a revenge tour=E2=80=94was parti=
cularly salient this week, amid reports that the Biden administration has d=
iscussed offering
preemptive blanket pardons to likely Trump targets. Schiff, who participate=
d in the January 6 investigation himself, is one such potential target, but=
 said he believed pardons would be =E2=80=9Cunnecessary=E2=80=9D because th=
e committee=E2=80=99s work was all above board. He also warned that =E2=80=
=9Cgiving preemptive blanket pardons on the way out of an administration I =
think is a precedent we don=E2=80=99t want to set.=E2=80=9D

Romney, too, is a possible target=E2=80=94he=E2=80=99s the only Republican =
senator who voted to impeach Trump twice. But he told Jake Tapper he wasn=
=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cparticularly worried about criminal investigations,=E2=
=80=9D musing that Trump=E2=80=99s they-oughta-be-in-jail rhetoric might ju=
st be hyperbole. He then made a better-angels appeal. =E2=80=9CI think Pres=
ident Trump is likely to try and focus on the future,=E2=80=9D he added. =
=E2=80=9CPeople who committed crimes, I=E2=80=99m sure, will be prosecuted.=
 But I think that=E2=80=99s few and far between.=E2=80=9D

Meanwhile, the fallout from Biden=E2=80=99s pardon
of his son Hunter continues, even within his own party. Sanders called it =
=E2=80=9Ckind of a dangerous=E2=80=9D precedent =E2=80=9Cas a very wide-ope=
n pardon which could under different circumstances lead to problems in term=
s of future presidents.=E2=80=9D And on Face the Nation, Minnesota Democrat=
ic Sen. Amy Klobuchar said =E2=80=9Cthis whole process cries out for reform=
 because otherwise you undermine the justice system. =E2=80=A6 Let=E2=80=99=
s at least look at these on a factual basis and a risk basis, instead of ju=
st in the middle of the night a month before a president leaves.=E2=80=9D

